Law students handle cases at new Health Law Clinic

Byjohn B. Moore
Staﬂ’ Writer

The denial of health care beneﬁts from programs like
Medicare, Medicaid and private insurance companies. is
a tragic reality to many. But when a person is then
unable to legally pursue the government and private
companies in the hopes of regaining the lost beneﬁts,
the problem intensiﬁes.

Recognizing this problem, the University of
Pittsburgh School of Law has established the Health
Law Clinic.

Receiving funds from the U.S. Department of
Education, the Health Law Clinic provides free legal
services to impoverished persons who have had health
care beneﬁts denied.

The clinic, which opened on Jan. 10, is staffed by 10

third-year law students who have been certiﬁed by the
Pennsylvania Supreme Court to represent consenting
clients. They are supervised by Stella Smetanka
and Karen Engro, assistant clinical professors of law at
Pitt.

Receiving seven credits for their work at the clinic,
the law students meet for seven hours a week in the
classroom and then must work at least six hours a
week in the clinic, talking to clients, meeting with doc-
tors and researching medical histories.

“Clinical experience is a good thing for last-year law
students,” said Smetanka.

“We advise that {the students] only take two other
courses during the semester. Some are also holding
down part-time positions at law firms.”

The services provided by the law students mainly
deal with cases involving denial of benefits through

Medicare, Medicaid, Supplemental Security Income
programs, managed care programs and private insur-
ance contracts.

“The students come from all different perspectives of
health care. One student was even a nurse  we’re all
helping the disabled and people with health care
needs,” said Smetanka.

Although the Health Law Clinic is there to help oth-
ers, it has set out to target children with AIDS, the frail
elderly, pregnant women and people with disabilities
as clients.

“Pittsburgh has a great need [for the clinic], with its
changing population,” said Smetanka. “The Health Law
Clinic is a natural follow-up to some of the other clin-
ics.”

