Concerned parents hurt country

The volatile health care debate is now facing a major
hurdle that may hold up the whole works.

The new hurdle is an old problem. The never-ending
abortion debate, which by now has very little new to
add to politics, may make its next contribution to the
American political scene by locking up the chances for
real health care reform.

USA Today reports that both sides of the abortion
debate are mobilizing their forces in order to make
sure their agenda is carried out in legislation.

Planned Parenthood is launching a ten-million-dollar
advertising campaign in order to. make sure congress
provides for two things. They want congress to allo-
cate health-care money for birth control and they also
want the health—care plan to pay_ for abortions.

Concerned Women for America, the largest women’s
group in America comprised of 600,000 members, is
pushing to extract promises from senators. They want
the senators to pledge not to vote for any health-care
reform bill that covers abortions.

What we are seeing again is an old debate which has
raged on without any decisive result. What is at stake
here is the health of this entire nation. The United
States has the highest health-care costs of the entire
industrialized world. The obscene costs of health care
are hurting the entire country on several levels. The
costs are hurting our international competitiveness and
productivity levels. A healthy population is the best
asset this country could have. Health-care reform is the
answer.

Both of these groups claim they are trying to help
the women of this country. One must wonder if that is
their true goal. Instead of helping all women obtain a
higher standard of living and better health care, they
are willing to throw the whole issue of health—care
reform into gridlock over this one issue. The outra-
geous thing is that there is not even a consensus of
opinion throughout either group.

How can this country allow people to remain unin-
sured and be forced into dire economic straits because
of health care over a single issue. It is a gross abuse of
our system that these two groups, simply because of
their command of political resources, can hurt so many
people by ending chances of health—care reform.

Can we allow this important issue, which will
already take years to resolve, be held up by two spe-
cial-interest groups? What the citizens of this country
are faced with is a case of two groups shaping the
entire future of the nation. The focus on more substan-
tive issues is lost in a highly emotional debate. This is

not only undemocratic, but also just plain foolish. Both‘

groups should take a minute to realize the irnmensely—
improved benefits all women will receive with the pas-
sage of reform.

   
  

